<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-746-116  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 746 116.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 30 1990 v7 n31 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Some question FCC ability to dictate int'l rate reforms: observerssay FCC may not have legal authority.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communication Commission's (FCC) initiative to lowerinternational switched service prices is raising serious questionsover its ability to effect regulatory reforms for services thatare provided, in part, by foreign carriers.andP;  The FCC claims thatcarriers are charging much more than the cost of providing theservices and outlined specific reforms to lower the paymentscarriers make to each other for terminations of internationalswitched traffic.andP;  Reducing these payments will result in lowercosts to carriers, reduce user charges, and lessen the US tradedeficit in international switched services.andP;  The FCC may not havethe legal authority to accomplish these goals, as they wouldrequire foreign carriers to cooperate with a US agency.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International CommunicationsSwitching CentersTelephone CompaniesForeign CompetitionPrice CuttingUnited States. Federal Communications Commission.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Cutting the cost of calls abroad. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>